{{Infobox person | name = Larry J. Cruz | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1941|9|17|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2008|2|4|1941|9|17|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States of America|U.S.A.]] | other_names = | known_for = founder of LJC Restaurant Group | occupation = [[journalist]], [[restaurant|restaurateur]]}}
'''Lorenzo "Larry" J. Cruz''' (September 17, 1941 – feb. 8, 2008) was a [[Philippines|Filipino]] restaurateur who founded the LJC Restaurant Group, which operates several restaurants in the Philippines.<ref name=mt>{{cite news |title=Larry J. Cruz |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2008/feb/06/yehey/opinion/20080206opi1.html |work=Editorial |publisher=Manila Times |date=2008-02-06 |accessdate=2008-03-18 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080312003736/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2008/feb/06/yehey/opinion/20080206opi1.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-03-12}}</ref> Among the restaurants he established through the LJC Group were ''Café Adriatico'', ''Cafe Havana'', ''Bistro Remedios'', and ''Abe'', which was named after his father, the writer [[E. Aguilar Cruz]].<ref name=mt2>{{cite news|author=Larry Cruz |title=My Mother Fely J |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/may/13/yehey/weekend/20070513week2.html |publisher=Manila Times |date=2007-05-13 |accessdate=2008-04-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005233036/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/may/13/yehey/weekend/20070513week2.html |archivedate=October 5, 2008 }}</ref> Cruz was also a journalist and magazine publisher.
Before entering the restaurant business, Cruz was a reporter for the [[Manila Times]] and the [[Philippine Herald]]. In the 1960s, he joined the staff of a Hong Kong-based magazine. In the early years of the administration of [[President of the Philippines|Philippine President]] [[Ferdinand Marcos]], Cruz was a member of the presidential press office.<ref name=mt/>
Cruz, who was not a chef himself, established Café Adriatico in [[Malate, Manila]] in 1979.<ref name=inq/> The venture proved successful and helped revitalize the Malate area, other restaurants and cafes opening in the vicinity in the midst of the Adriatico's success. Cruz expanded his restaurant business with the opening of several other restaurants within [[Metro Manila]] through the LJC Restaurant Group. At the time of his death in 2008, Cruz had opened fourteen restaurants in the Philippines. Several of his restaurants featured Filipino and Kapampangan cuisine.
In the late 1980s, Cruz published ''Metro Magazine'', a city guide/political/lifestyle magazine inspired by ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]'' and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.<ref name=inq2>{{cite news |author=Thelma Sioson San Juan |title=Larry can't cook |url=http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20080207-117427/Larry-cant-cook |publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=2008-02-07 |accessdate=2008-04-16 }}</ref> He later sold the magazine to [[Eugenio Lopez Jr.]] in order to finance the expansion of his restaurants.<ref name=inq2/>
Upon his death on February 4, 2008, following complications from cancer, Cruz was hailed at the time of his death as the leading Filipino "pioneer in theme or concept restaurants" and the man who had "shaped Philippine café society".<ref name=inq>{{cite news |author=Thelma Sioson San Juan |title=Larry Cruz, restaurateur, journalist, dies in US; 66 |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080205-116845/Larry-Cruz-restaurateur-journalist-dies-in-US-66 |publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=2008-02-05 |accessdate=2008-03-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207055843/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080205-116845/Larry-Cruz-restaurateur-journalist-dies-in-US-66 |archivedate=2008-02-07 |df= }}</ref>
