'''Miguel Santiago''' is an [[American people|American]] [[politician]], currently serving in the [[California State Assembly]], where he serves as chairman of the Communications and Conveyance Committee.<ref>http://acom.assembly.ca.gov/</ref> Santiago is a [[California Democratic Party|Democrat]] representing the [[California's 53rd State Assembly district|53rd Assembly District]], which encompasses parts of [[Downtown Los Angeles]] and [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]].

Santiago is a member of the California Latino Legislative Caucus.<ref>http://latinocaucus.legislature.ca.gov/member-directory</ref> Prior to being elected to the Assembly in 2014, he was a member of the [[Los Angeles Community College District]] Board of Trustees.<ref>http://laccd.edu/Board/Pages/Miguel-Santiago.aspx</ref> He also served as District Director to former [[List of Speakers of the California State Assembly|Assembly Speaker]] [[John A. Perez|John Pérez]].<ref>https://www.laccd.edu/Board/PublishingImages/Miguel-Santiago.aspx</ref>

==Net Neutrality Bill Co-Authorship==
Santiago co-authored [https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB822 S.B. 822] alongside Senator [[Scott Wiener]], legislation that would strengthen [[Net neutrality in the United States|net neutrality]] protections in California. Hours after being signed into law by Governor [[Jerry Brown]], a Motion for Preliminary [[Injunction]] was filed by the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]]. Both parties have agreed to wait until a separate court case in the D.C. Circuit Court is decided before moving on. As part of the agreement, the law is not currently being enforced and the injunction was withdrawn. 

After passing the [[California_State_Senate|California Senate]],<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billVotesClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB822|title=Bill Votes|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> S.B. 822 was amended by Miguel Santiago in June 2018.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/06/20/us/ap-us-net-neutrality-california.html</ref>  SB-822 would restore [[Barack Obama|Obama]]-era rules that the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]-controlled [[Federal Communications Commission]] rolled back in December, 2017.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://biglawbusiness.com/lawmaker-changes-cloud-calif-net-neutrality-bill-outlook/|title=Lawmaker Changes Cloud Calif. Net Neutrality Bill Outlook|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en-US}}</ref> Santiago's amendments removed all provisions of the bill's net neutrality protections that were not in the text of the 2015 Open Internet Order, leaving in only those that were in the two-pages of rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cyberlaw.stanford.edu/blog/2018/06/failing-real-test-sb-822-no-longer-restores-all-lost-net-neutrality-protections|title=Failing the Real Test: SB 822 No Longer Restores All the Lost Net Neutrality Protections|website=cyberlaw.stanford.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-06-28}}</ref> This prompted the bill's original sponsor, Senator Scott Wiener, to pull his support for his own bill and declare that it had been "hijacked" and that he was "not interested in passing a bill that is watered down so severely." <ref>https://www.commondreams.org/news/2018/06/20/telecom-backed-democrat-california-just-mutilated-nations-strongest-state-net</ref> The changes also included deleting a large section of definitions, which critics claim could make it more difficult for California's attorney general to prosecute violations of the legislation.<ref name=":1">https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2018/06/20/californias-net-neutrality-legislation-just-got-watered-down-in-a-big-way/</ref> 

The amendments, published less than 12 hours before the hearing, were approved 8-0[6] by the Communications and Conveyance committee, which Santiago chairs, on June 20, 2018. That vote occurred before Wiener could argue against them and before any testimony. After the testimony, the amended bill was approved 8-2.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sd11.senate.ca.gov/news/20180620-senator-wiener%E2%80%99s-statement-gutting-net-neutrality-bill-assembly-committee|title=Senator Wiener’s Statement on Gutting of Net Neutrality Bill in Assembly Committee|date=2018-06-20|work=Senator Scott Wiener|access-date=2018-06-28|language=en}}</ref><ref>https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2018/06/rampant-corruption-assembly-committee-gutted-californias-net-neutrality</ref> Opponents of the amended version stated that Santiago's changes would create loopholes through which [[Internet service provider|broadband providers]] could charge fees to content providers while exempting their own content from any data caps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billVotesClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB822|title=Bill Votes|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|access-date=2018-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calchannel.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=7&clip_id=5632|title=Assembly Communications and Conveyance Committee  - Jun 20th, 2018|website=calchannel.granicus.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-28}}</ref><ref>http://www.latimes.com/opinion/la-ol-enter-the-fray-net-neutrality-bill-neutered-in-the-fine-1529530738-htmlstory.html</ref><ref>https://www.wired.com/story/california-net-neutrality-bill-was-hijacked-lawmaker-says/</ref> Proponents of the changes contend that without them broadband providers would not be allowed to offer free mobile data that doesn't count against users' caps, harming consumers, and that net neutrality in general would discourage providers from improving their [[Internet_backbone#Infrastructure|network infrastructure]].<ref>http://www.sacbee.com/opinion/op-ed/article213519679.html</ref><ref name=":1" /> Representatives of major ISPs continue to oppose the bill, even in its amended form.<ref name=":0" /> 

State Assemblyman Miguel Santiago has received over $60,000 from telecom [[lobbyists]], with [[AT&T]] and [[Comcast]] being the top telecom contributors, over the course of his assembly career.<ref>https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1QcUCKnY7pDPf4iSLuyk3xgFei33JySJhAFV1w5OMMz8/edit#gid=0</ref><ref>https://votesmart.org/candidate/campaign-finance/151853/miguel-santiago#.WyhL_xJKhE4%5D</ref> However, Wiener said that despite the "strenuous disagreement here, [...] it’s not about campaign contributions" and that the telecoms "spent a lot of money in California targeting members with Twitter and Facebook ads, doing robo-calls to seniors telling them their bills are going to go up, that this bill is going to make your monthly payment go up. They flooded the capitol with lobbyists."<ref name=":1" />

On June 6, 2018, Santiago released a [https://a53.asmdc.org/press-releases/20180622-assemblymember-miguel-santiago-issues-statement-net-neutrality press statement] saying that his amendments were intended to help "deliver a bill that could withstand legal challenges from the telecommunications industry" and that "we ran out of time" to reach an agreement with Wiener. Knowing Wiener would not support the changes, the committee "took action to insert amendments without his consent to keep the bill moving." Santiago expressed regret at the "legislative maneuverings" required to advance the bill and that he does not "envision policy being created in this manner." The public response was intense, and Santiago stated that his family had received threats and that offensive memes smearing his wife and children had been shared online. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://a53.asmdc.org/press-releases/20180622-assemblymember-miguel-santiago-issues-statement-net-neutrality|title=Assemblymember Miguel Santiago Issues Statement on Net Neutrality|date=2018-06-22|work=Official Website - Assemblymember Miguel Santiago Representing the 53rd California Assembly District|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/business/national-business/article213665394.html|title=California lawmaker faces harsh attacks over net neutrality|work=charlotteobserver|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en}}</ref>

