{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}
'''Richard Bowker''' [[CBE]] (born 1966) is the current chairman of [[UK Athletics]] and independent director of the [[English Football League]]. He is a former [[chief executive]] of [[National Express]] and [[Etihad Railway]] and former chairman and chief executive of the [[Strategic Rail Authority]]. He attended [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Blackburn]], read economics at [[Leicester University]], and played as a professional session pianist for a year.  Bowker is a chartered management accountant and was a non-executive director of [[British Waterways]] <ref>[http://www.nationalexpressgroup.com/nx_as2006/services/downloads/bod_compsecretary.pdf 11646_NX<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and of the [[London Marathon]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1051633/bowker-takes-over-from-warner-as-chairman-of-uk-athletics-two-months-early | accessdate=2018-01-01 | title=Bowker takes over from Warner as chairman of UK Athletics two months early }}</ref> In the 2004 New Year's Honours List, he was awarded a  CBE.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.independent.co.uk/business/news/article26639.ece | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130827013222/http://news.independent.co.uk/business/news/article26639.ece | dead-url=yes | archive-date=2013-08-27 | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Damian | last=Reece | title=Knighthoods go to CBI's Digby Jones and OFT's John Vickers | date=2004-12-31 }}</ref>

In 1989 he joined the London Underground as a graduate finance trainee; in the course of this work, he was credited with the launch of a new leasing system for trains in 1997.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3407783.stm | work=BBC News | title=Profile: Richard Bowker | date=2004-01-18}}</ref> Bowker was appointed co-chairman of [[Virgin Rail Group]] in 1999 and commercial director of the [[Virgin Group]] in 2000. He also founded the transport consultancy Quasar Associated.

In 2001 he was appointed chairman and chief executive of the [[Strategic Rail Authority]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/business/story/0,,581954,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Don't rail saviours look young nowadays? | date=2001-10-28}}</ref> In 2006, he was appointed chief executive of National Express Group. 
From 2009 to 2012 he acted as chief executive of [[Etihad Railway]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaeinteract.com/docs/Union_Railway_in_UAE_marks_the_beginning_of_an_era_of_long-term_investment_Al_Nowais/40081.htm
|accessdate=2010-09-11
|title=Union Railway in UAE marks the beginning of an era of long-term investment: Al Nowais UAE - The Official Web Site - News
}}</ref>
<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/middle-east/richard-bowker-quits-etihad-rail.html | accessdate=2018-01-01 | title=Richard Bowker Quits Etihad Rail: International Railway Journal
}}</ref>

In 2012 he was appointed as the second ever independent non-executive director of the [[English Football League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2013/june/richard-bowker-cbe/ | accessdate=2018-01-01 | title=Richard Bowker CBE: English Football League}}</ref>. In 2017 he replaced Ed Warner as chairman of [[UK Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1051633/bowker-takes-over-from-warner-as-chairman-of-uk-athletics-two-months-early | accessdate=2018-01-01 | title=Bowker takes over from Warner as chairman of UK Athletics two months early }}</ref>

