{{Infobox person | name = Serge Pun | native_name = {{my|သိမ်းဝေ}} | native_name_lang = my | other_names = Theim Wai | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{b-da|1953}} | birth_place = [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]] | nationality = Burmese | occupation = | networth = [[United States dollar|US$]]500 million (2013)<ref name="fbs">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/serge-pun/|title=Serge Pun|date=August 2013|work=Forbes Asia|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> | spouse = | children = 4 (inc. Cyrus Pun) | residence = | religion = | alma_mater = [[Basic Education High School No. 6 Botataung|St. Paul's English High School]]<ref name="ften">{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f9093c8a-f8cd-11e1-b4ba-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2dfH2bvDX|title=A business school of hard knocks|last=Robinson|first=Gwen|date=9 September 2012|work=Financial Times|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> | website = | parents = }}
'''Serge Pun''' ({{lang-my|သိမ်းဝေ}}, Theim Wai;<ref name=forbes>{{cite journal | last=Montlake | first=Simon | work=Forbes Asia | title=Golden Return: Serge Pun Constructs A Real-Estate Empire In Myanmar | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/simonmontlake/2013/08/28/golden-return-serge-pun-constructs-a-real-estate-empire-in-myanmar/ | date=2013-08-28}}</ref> {{zh|t=潘繼澤|p=Pān Jìzé}};<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ftchinese.com/story/001046842|title=缅甸大亨潘继泽的艰辛奋斗史|date=8 October 2012|work=Financial Times|language=Chinese|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> born 1953 in [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]]) is a Burmese businessman of Burmese-Chinese descent. He is the chairman of [[Serge Pun & Associates]] Group (SPA Group), a multinational real estate firm, and [[Yoma Bank]], a Burma-based bank.<ref name="spa">{{cite web|url=http://www.spa-myanmar.com/about-us/board-of-directors.html|title=Serge Pun|work=SPA|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> Born in Burma, he migrated to [[Beijing]] in 1965, 3 years following the coup d'état by [[Ne Win]] and subsequent reprisals on foreign residents.<ref name="az">{{cite news|url=http://www2.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=5010&page=7|title=Tycoon Turf|last=Aung Zaw|date=September 2005|work=The Irrawaddy|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> In 1973, he left China for [[Hong Kong]], where he began a career in real estate.<ref name="az"/> Pun returned to Burma in 1991 to establish SPA Myanmar, which is now one of Burma's largest conglomerates, spanning several sectors including automobile manufacturing, financial services, real estate development, technology, construction and healthcare.<ref name="az"/> Pun's brother, Martin Pun, is the vice chairman of SPA Group.<ref name="spa"/>
Pun was ranked #38 in Singapore's Richest 50 in the August 2013 issue of ''[[Forbes Asia]]'', with a net worth of USD $500 million.<ref name="fbs"/>
